{{italic title}} The '''''Ruijū Karin''''' (類聚歌林) was a Japanese ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' anthology compiled by [[Yamanoue no Okura]].
== Compilation and date == The ''Ruijū Karin'' was compiled by [[Yamanoue no Okura]].{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} It was likely compiled after [[Yōrō|Yōrō 5]] (721) when Okura become a tutor to the [[crown prince of Japan|crown prince]] (later [[Emperor Shōmu]]).{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}}
== Title == The work's title has been translated into English as:<!-- These come from a quick GBooks search of "Ruiju Karin". Most of the sources are well-regarded. Not sure about how this should be formatted in the long term; probably Japanese sources have speculated at length about the meaning and origin of the title, for which discussion we would need to explain its basic meaning, and one or more of the below published translations would be useful. --> *''The Grove of Poetry, Arranged by Topic'' *''Forest of Classified Verse'' *''Forest of Classified Verses'' *''The Grove of Poems Classified'' *''Classified Forest of Poetry'' *''Classified Forest of Verse'' <!-- Do not add "grove of arranged trees" from https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=y4lZAAAAMAAJ&q=ruiju+karin&dq=ruiju+karin&hl=ja&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiasMyGyureAhUGxLwKHcikAVA4ChDoAQg6MAM here, as the source is clearly flawed, its author apparently not even knowing 万 doesn't mean "a thousand". Same goes for "The Forest of Choice Bamboos" from the obviously bogus "Japan Encyclopedia". -->
== Status and apparent contents == The work is now lost.{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}}
It apparently survived until around the end of the [[Heian period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} The late-Heian [[karonsho|books of poetic criticism]] ''{{illm|Yakumo Mishō|ja|八雲御抄}}''{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994|2a1=Imura|2y=1998}} and ''{{illm|Fukuro-zōshi|ja|袋草紙}}''{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}} record that copies of it were in the holdings of [[Byōdō-in]]{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}} and/or [[Hōjō-ji]]{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}}), and in addition to these works{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} it was also mentioned in a diary entry from 1015 (永承五年四月二十六日前麗景殿女御延子歌絵合, 正子内親王絵合),{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} ''[[Ōgishō]]'' (奥義抄),{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} [[Fujiwara no Shunzei]]'s ''{{illm|Korai Fūteishō|ja|古来風体抄}}'',{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} ''[[Waka Genzaisho Mokuroku]]'' (和歌現在書目録),{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} ''{{illm|Waka Iroha|ja|和歌色葉}}'',{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}} but none of these works quote it directly.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichinose|1y=1991|1p=73}}
Its contents are now known only from nine fragmentary passages{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994|2a1=Imura|2y=1998}} quoted in books [[Man'yōshū Book I|I]], [[Man'yōshū Book II|II]] and [[Man'yōshū Book IX|IX]] the ''[[Man'yōshū]]'',{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}} as a source of information poets and the circumstances of composition of poems,{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} and its full contents are unknown.{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} The number of books which comprised the anthology is unknown,{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} although the [[Shōsōin]] supposedly included a '''''Karin Nanakan''''' (歌林七巻){{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} copied by {{illm|Prince Ichihara|ja|市原王}}{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}} which, if it was the same as this work, would mean it consisted of seven books.{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}}
The work divided poems into categories based on some sort of criteria{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} and, using resources such as the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' and ''[[Fudoki]]'',{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} investigated the circumstances under which its poems were composed.{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} As far as the ''Man'yōshū'' tells us, it apparently included poems by [[emperor of Japan|emperors]]{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} and [[imperial family of Japan|members of the imperial family]],{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} as well as court poems such as those commemorating imperial processions to various parts of the country (行幸従駕 ''gyōkō-jūga'').{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}} This has led to the theory that it was compiled to be presented to the crown prince.{{sfnm|1a1=Endō|1y=1994}}
It may have been modeled on the Chinese work ''[[Yiwen Leiju]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Imura|1y=1998}}
