An '''usher''' is a person who shows people where to sit, especially at a theatre or when attending a wedding. An example of an usher is a person who is friends with the groom who directs people where to sit as they enter the church for a wedding.

[[File:Princess Museum Edmonton Ushers.jpg|thumb|right|[[Princess Theatre (Edmonton)|Princess Theatre]] Ushers]]

==History==
The word comes from the [[Latin]] ''[[wikt:ostiarius|ostiarius]]'' ("porter", "doorman") through Norman French, and is a cognate of the French ''[[:fr:Huissier|huissier]]''. 

Ushers were servants or [[courtier]]s who showed or ushered visitors in and out of meetings in large houses or palaces.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

In the [[United Kingdom]], a variety of titles for courtiers in the [[Royal Household]] include the word ''usher''. In [[England]], [[Wales]], [[Scotland]] and [[Ireland]], from the early sixteenth century until at least the end of the nineteenth century, the term denoted an assistant to a schoolmaster or head-teacher; an under-master, assistant-master.<ref name="OEDUsher">{{cite web |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/220658?rskey=WqlPa7&result=1 |title=usher, n.|publisher=OED Online|accessdate=2013-07-25|format= |work= }}</ref> In such use, however, the term is now rare.<ref name="OEDUsher" />

==Duties==
{{globalize/US|section|date=June 2016}}
[[File:The Republic exhibition - NM Prague 14.JPG|thumb|right|Cinema ticket. The usher checks the tickets in the entrance of cinemas and theaters, directing visitors to their seat and assists people who sit in the wrong place]]
Ushers assist visitors by formally showing the way in a large building or to their appropriate seats. This may coincide with a security role.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

At weddings, friends of the groom and bride may be recruited to direct guests at the ceremony, and generally be available for assistance.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

Ushers help those in attendance at entertainment and sporting events in theatres and stadiums. Duties include checking tickets, directing people to their assigned seats, distributing programmes, answering questions and assisting people in finding restrooms and refreshments.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

According to the [[United States Department of Labor]], ushers, lobby attendants and ticket takers earn an average wage of $8.41 an hour and $17,500 a year. Approximately 102,000 are employed in this line of work. Most of these workers are employed by the motion picture and video industries, secondly they work in the performing arts and sporting events venues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes393031.htm |title=Occupational Employment and Wages, May 2006 |accessdate=2008-02-06 |work= }}</ref>

Other jobs also come under the name 'Usher', such as baseball field personnel. A field usher coordinates not only the baseball diamond grounds but also the stadium itself.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

Ushers are also expected to help with security and to ensure that only people with proper authority have access to backstage areas. Ushers also monitor the crowds and can summon security when needed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes393031.htm |title=Careers: Ushers and Ticket Takers |accessdate=2008-02-06 |work= }}</ref>

In [[Movie theater|cinema]]s and theaters, it was common for ushers to check tickets and show people to their seats to watch the film being shown. If actually during the film, when lights were dimmed, the usher would shine a [[Flashlight|torch]] to light the row of seating in question.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

